===subject:reply
===from:Bethany Ballard
===date:Tue Mar 25 18:53:47 2003
===message:I think you brought up a good point in stating that politicians were afraid of hurting their career if pursuing further legislation for the freedmen.  So many of the politicians and the President himself, were more concerned about how their popularity would be affected and they wanted to ensure themselves re-election votes for the next term.  Therefore, I think the politicians' trying to please the south and the white man, had a lot to do, along with the fact that the laws were not enforced, with the reason why reconstruction was not as successful as it could have been.  But to say that reconstruction was a total failure, in my opinion, isn't true, because even though the laws were not enforced as they should have been, it gave all black men freedom, which would change their lives forever.   
=========yorg=========
